[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In computer science, **analysis of parallel algorithms** is the process of finding the computational complexity of algorithms executed in parallel – the amount of time, storage, or other resources needed to execute them.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In many respects, analysis of parallel algorithms is similar to the analysis of sequential algorithms, but is generally more involved because one must reason about the behavior of multiple cooperating threads of execution.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] One of the primary goals of parallel analysis is to understand how a parallel algorithm's use of resources (speed, space, etc.) changes as the number of processors is changed.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] A so-called work-time (WT) (sometimes called work-depth, or work-span) framework was originally introduced by Shiloach and Vishkin for conceptualizing and describing parallel algorithms.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In the WT framework, a parallel algorithm is first described in terms of parallel rounds.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For each round, the operations to be performed are characterized, but several issues can be suppressed.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For example, the number of operations at each round need not be clear, processors need not be mentioned and any information that may help with the assignment of processors to jobs need not be accounted for.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Second, the suppressed information is provided.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The inclusion of the suppressed information is guided by the proof of a scheduling theorem due to Brent, which is explained later in this article.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The WT framework is useful since while it can greatly simplify the initial description of a parallel algorithm, inserting the details suppressed by that initial description is often not very difficult.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For example, the WT framework was adopted as the basic presentation framework in the parallel algorithms books (for the parallel random-access machine PRAM model) and, as well as in the class notes .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The overview below explains how the WT framework can be used for analyzing more general parallel algorithms, even when their description is not available within the WT framework.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Suppose computations are executed on a machine that has p processors.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Let Tp denote the time that expires between the start of the computation and its end.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Analysis of parallel algorithms is usually carried out under the assumption that an unbounded number of processors is available.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] This is unrealistic, but not a problem, since any computation that can run in parallel on N processors can be executed on *p* < *N* processors by letting each processor execute multiple units of work.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] showing that the span (depth) *T*∞ and the work *T*1 together provide reasonable bounds on the computation time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] In computational complexity theory, the **exponential time hypothesis** or **ETH** is an unproven computational hardness assumption that was formulated by Impagliazzo & Paturi (1999).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] It states that satisfiability of 3-CNF Boolean formulas (3-SAT) cannot be solved in subexponential time, $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] More precisely, the usual form of the hypothesis asserts the existence of a number $s_{3}>0$ such that all algorithms that correctly solve 3-SAT require time at least $2^{s_{3}n}.$ The exponential time hypothesis, if true, would imply that P ≠ NP, but it is a stronger statement.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Beyond NP-complete problems, it implies that many known algorithms (including those with lower than exponential time) have optimal or near-optimal time complexity.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The k -SAT problem is a version of the Boolean satisfiability problem in which the input to the problem is a Boolean expression in conjunctive normal form (that is, an *and* of *ors* of variables and their negations) with at most k variables per clause.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The goal is to determine whether this expression can be made to be true by some assignment of Boolean values to its variables.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] 2-SAT has a linear time algorithm, but all known algorithms for larger k take exponential time, with the base of the exponential function depending on k .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] For instance, the WalkSAT probabilistic algorithm can solve k -SAT in average time $\left(2-{\frac {2}{k}}\right)^{n}n^{O(1)},$ where n is the number of variables in the given k -SAT instance.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] For each integer $k\geq 3$ , define $s_{k}$ to be the smallest number such that k -SAT can be solved in time $2^{s_{k}n+o(n)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] This minimum might not exist, if a sequence of better and better algorithms have correspondingly smaller exponential growth in their time bounds; in that case, define $s_{k}$ to be the infimum of the real numbers $\delta$ for which k -SAT can be solved in time $O(2^{\delta n})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Some sources define the exponential time hypothesis to be the slightly weaker statement that 3-SAT cannot be solved in time $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] If there existed an algorithm to solve 3-SAT in time $2^{o(n)}$ , then $s_{3}$ would equal zero.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] If this were to be the case, then $s_{3}$ would equal zero even though there would be no single algorithm running in time $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] A related variant of the exponential time hypothesis is the **non-uniform exponential time hypothesis**, which posits that there is no family of algorithms (one for each length of the input, in the spirit of advice) that can solve 3-SAT in time $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Because the numbers $s_{3},s_{4},\dots$ form a monotonic sequence that is bounded above by one, they must converge to a limit $s_{\infty }=\lim _{k\to \infty }s_{k}.$ The **strong exponential time hypothesis** (SETH) is the conjecture that $s_{\infty }=1$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] It is not possible for $s_{k}$ to equal $s_{\infty }$ for any finite k : as Impagliazzo, Paturi & Zane (2001) showed, there exists a constant $\alpha$ such that $s_{k}\leq s_{\infty }(1-\alpha /k)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, if the exponential time hypothesis is true, there must be infinitely many values of k for which $s_{k}$ differs from $s_{k+1}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, if 3-SAT could be solved in subexponential time, one could use this reduction to solve k -SAT in subexponential time as well.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Equivalently, if $s_{k}>0$ for any $k>0$ , then $s_{3}>0$ as well, and the exponential time hypothesis would be true.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, if the strong exponential time hypothesis is true, then there would be no algorithm for general CNF satisfiability that is significantly faster than a brute-force search over all possible truth assignments.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] However, if the strong exponential time hypothesis fails, it would still be possible for $s_{\operatorname {CNF} }$ to equal one.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis implies that many other problems in the complexity class SNP do not have algorithms whose running time is faster than $c^{n}$ for some constant c .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] These problems include graph k-colorability, finding Hamiltonian cycles, maximum cliques, maximum independent sets, and vertex cover on n -vertex graphs.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Conversely, if any of these problems has a subexponential algorithm, then the exponential time hypothesis could be shown to be false.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] If cliques or independent sets of logarithmic size could be found in polynomial time, the exponential time hypothesis would be false.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, even though finding cliques or independent sets of such small size is unlikely to be NP-complete, the exponential time hypothesis implies that these problems are non-polynomial.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] More generally, the exponential time hypothesis implies that it is not possible to find cliques or independent sets of size k in time $n^{o(k)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis also implies that it is not possible to solve the k-SUM problem (given n real numbers, find k of them that add to zero) in time $n^{o(k)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The strong exponential time hypothesis implies that it is not possible to find k -vertex dominating sets more quickly than in time $n^{k-o(1)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis implies also that the weighted feedback arc set problem on tournaments does not have a parametrized algorithm with running time ${\textstyle O(2^{o({\sqrt {\operatorname {OPT} }})}n^{O(1)})}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] It does however have a parameterized algorithm with running time ${\textstyle O(2^{O({\sqrt {\operatorname {OPT} }})}n^{O(1)})}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The strong exponential time hypothesis leads to tight bounds on the parameterized complexity of several graph problems on graphs of bounded treewidth.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Equivalently, any improvement on these running times would falsify the strong exponential time hypothesis.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis also implies that any fixed-parameter tractable algorithm for edge clique cover must have double exponential dependence on the parameter.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] In the three-party set disjointness problem in communication complexity, three subsets of the integers in some range $[1,m]$ are specified, and three communicating parties each know two of the three subsets.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The goal is for the parties to transmit as few bits to each other on a shared communications channel in order for one of the parties to be able to determine whether the intersection of the three sets is empty or nonempty.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] A trivial m -bit communications protocol would be for one of the three parties to transmit a bitvector describing the intersection of the two sets known to that party, after which either of the two remaining parties can determine the emptiness of the intersection.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] However, if there exists a protocol that solves the problem with $o(m)$ communication and $2^{o(m)}$ computation, it could be transformed into an algorithm for solving k -SAT in time $O(1.74^{n})$ for any fixed constant k , violating the strong exponential time hypothesis.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, the strong exponential time hypothesis implies either that the trivial protocol for three-party set disjointness is optimal, or that any better protocol requires an exponential amount of computation.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] If the exponential time hypothesis is true, then 3-SAT would not have a polynomial time algorithm, and therefore it would follow that P ≠ NP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] More strongly, in this case, 3-SAT could not even have a quasi-polynomial time algorithm, so NP could not be a subset of QP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] However, if the exponential time hypothesis fails, it would have no implication for the P versus NP problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] In parameterized complexity theory, because the exponential time hypothesis implies that there does not exist a fixed-parameter-tractable algorithm for maximum clique, it also implies that W[1] ≠ FPT.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] It is an important open problem in this area whether this implication can be reversed: does W[1] ≠ FPT imply the exponential time hypothesis?
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis is equivalent to the statement that M[1] ≠ FPT, and the question of whether ${\mathsf {M}}[i]\subseteq {\mathsf {W}}[i]$ for $i>1$ is also open.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] It is also possible to prove implications in the other direction, from the failure of a variation of the strong exponential time hypothesis to separations of complexity classes.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] As Williams (2010) shows, if there exists an algorithm A that solves Boolean circuit satisfiability in time $2^{n}/f(n)$ for some superpolynomially growing function f , then NEXPTIME is not a subset of P/poly.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Williams shows that, if algorithm A exists, and a family of circuits simulating NEXPTIME in P/poly also existed, then algorithm A could be composed with the circuits to simulate NEXPTIME problems nondeterministically in a smaller amount of time, violating the time hierarchy theorem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, the existence of algorithm A proves the nonexistence of the family of circuits and the separation of these two complexity classes.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] It finds the exact solution to this problem, and to several related problems including the Hamiltonian cycle problem, in exponential time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] Number the cities $1,2,\ldots ,n$ , with 1 designated arbitrarily as a "starting" city (since the solution to TSP is a Hamiltonian cycle, the choice of starting city doesn't matter).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] The Held–Karp algorithm begins by calculating, for each set of cities $S\subseteq \{2,\ldots ,n\}$ and every city $e\neq 1$ not contained in S , the shortest one-way path from 1 to e that passes through every city in S in some order (but not through any other cities).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] Denote this distance $g(S,e)$ , and write $d(u,v)$ for the length of the direct edge from u to v .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] We'll compute values of $g(S,e)$ starting with the smallest sets S and finishing with the largest.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] When S has two or fewer elements, then calculating $g(S,e)$ requires looking at one or two possible shortest paths.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] For example, $g(\emptyset ,e)$ is simply $d(1,e)$ , and $g(\{2\},3)$ is just the length of $1\rightarrow 2\rightarrow 3$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] Likewise, $g(\{2,3\},4)$ is the length of either $1\rightarrow 2\rightarrow 3\rightarrow 4$ or $1\rightarrow 3\rightarrow 2\rightarrow 4$ , whichever is shorter.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] Once S contains three or more cities, the number of paths through S rises quickly, but only a few such paths need to be examined to find the shortest.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] More generally, suppose $S=\{s_{1},\ldots ,s_{k}\}$ is a set of k cities.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] Then if the shortest path from 1 through S to e has $s_{i}$ as its second-to-last city, then removing the final edge from this path must give the shortest path from 1 to $s_{i}$ through $S_{i}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] This means there are only k possible shortest paths from 1 to e through S , one for each possible second-to-last city $s_{i}$ with length $g(S_{i},s_{i})+d(s_{i},e)$ , and $g(S,e)=\min _{1\leq i\leq k}g(S_{i},s_{i})+d(s_{i},e)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] This stage of the algorithm finishes when $g(\{2,\ldots ,i-1,i+1,\ldots ,n\},i)$ is known for every integer $2\leq i\leq n$ , giving the shortest distance from city 1 to city i that passes through every other city.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] The much shorter second stage adds these distances to the edge lengths $d(i,1)$ to give $n-1$ possible shortest cycles, and then finds the shortest.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] The shortest path itself (and not just its length), finally, may be reconstructed by storing alongside $g(S,e)$ the label of the second-to-last city on the path from 1 to e through S , raising space requirements by only a constant factor.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] The Held–Karp algorithm has exponential time complexity $\Theta (2^{n}n^{2})$ , significantly better than the superexponential performance $\Theta (n!)$ of a brute-force algorithm.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] Held–Karp, however, requires $\Theta (n2^{n})$ space to hold all computed values of the function $g(S,e)$ , while brute force needs only $\Theta (n^{2})$ space to store the graph itself.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] Computing one value of $g(S,e)$ for a k -element subset S of $\{2,\ldots ,n\}$ requires finding the shortest of k possible paths, each found by adding a known value of g and an edge length from the original graph; that is, it requires time proportional to k .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] There are ${\textstyle {\binom {n-1}{k}}}$ k -element subsets of $\{2,\ldots ,n\}$ ; and each subset gives $n-k-1$ possible values of e .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] The second stage of the algorithm, finding a complete cycle from $n-1$ candidates, takes $\Theta (n)$ time and does not affect asymptotic performance.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] This is analogous to a bidirectional search starting at ${\textstyle 1}$ and meeting at midpoint ${\textstyle e}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] However, this is a constant factor improvement and does not affect asymptotic performance.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] Storing all values of $g(S,e)$ for subsets of size k requires keeping ${\textstyle (n-k-1){\binom {n-1}{k}}=(n-1){\binom {n-2}{k}}}$ values.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] This assumes that ${\textstyle n}$ is sufficiently small enough such that ${\textstyle S}$ can be stored as a bitmask of constant multiple of machine words, rather than an explicit k-tuple.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/held-karp-algorithm] If only the length of the shortest cycle is needed, not the cycle itself, then space complexity can be improved somewhat by noting that calculating $g(S,e)$ for a S of size k requires only values of g for subsets of size $k-1$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The **subset sum problem** (**SSP**) is a decision problem in computer science.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] In its most general formulation, there is a multiset S of integers and a target-sum T , and the question is to decide whether any subset of the integers sum to precisely T *.* The problem is known to be NP-complete.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] SSP can also be regarded as an optimization problem: find a subset whose sum is at most *T*, and subject to that, as close as possible to *T*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] It is NP-hard, but there are several algorithms that can solve it reasonably quickly in practice.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] SSP is a special case of the knapsack problem and of the multiple subset sum problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] As both *n* and *L* grow large, SSP is NP-hard.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The complexity of the best known algorithms is exponential in the smaller of the two parameters *n* and *L*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The problem is NP-hard even when all input integers are positive (and the target-sum *T* is a part of the input).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] This can be proved by a direct reduction from 3SAT.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The analogous counting problem #SSP, which asks to enumerate the number of subsets summing to the target, is #P-complete.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] There are several ways to solve SSP in time exponential in *n*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The most naïve algorithm would be to cycle through all subsets of *n* numbers and, for every one of them, check if the subset sums to the right number.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The running time is of order $O(2^{n}\cdot n)$ , since there are $2^{n}$ subsets and, to check each subset, we need to sum at most *n* elements.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The algorithm can be implemented by depth-first search of a binary tree: each level in the tree corresponds to an input number; the left branch corresponds to excluding the number from the set, and the right branch corresponds to including the number (hence the name Inclusion-Exclusion).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] In 1974, Horowitz and Sahni published a faster exponential-time algorithm, which runs in time $O(2^{n/2})$ , but requires much more space - $O(2^{n/2})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The algorithm splits arbitrarily the *n* elements into two sets of $n/2$ each.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] For each of these two sets, it stores a list of the sums of all $2^{n/2}$ possible subsets of its elements.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Using even the fastest comparison sorting algorithm, Mergesort for this step would take time $O(2^{n/2}n)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] However, given a sorted list of sums for k elements, the list can be expanded to two sorted lists with the introduction of a ( $k+1$ )th element, and these two sorted lists can be merged in time $O(2^{k})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Thus, each list can be generated in sorted form in time $O(2^{n/2})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Given the two sorted lists, the algorithm can check if an element of the first array and an element of the second array sum up to *T* in time $O(2^{n/2})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] To do that, the algorithm passes through the first array in decreasing order (starting at the largest element) and the second array in increasing order (starting at the smallest element).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Whenever the sum of the current element in the first array and the current element in the second array is more than *T*, the algorithm moves to the next element in the first array.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] If it is less than *T*, the algorithm moves to the next element in the second array.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] If two elements that sum to *T* are found, it stops.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] In 1981, Schroeppel and Shamir presented an algorithm based on Horowitz and Sanhi, that requires similar runtime - $O(2^{n/2}\cdot (n/4))$ , much less space - $O(2^{n/4})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Due to space requirements, the HS algorithm is practical for up to about 50 integers, and the SS algorithm is practical for up to 100 integers.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] In 2010, Howgrave-Graham and Joux presented a probabilistic algorithm that runs faster than all previous ones - in time $O(2^{0.337n})$ using space $O(2^{0.256n})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] It solves only the decision problem, cannot prove there is no solution for a given sum, and does not return the subset sum closest to *T*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The techniques of Howgrave-Graham and Joux were subsequently extended bringing the time complexity to $O(2^{0.291n})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] A more recent generalization lowered the time complexity to $O(2^{0.283n})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] SSP can be solved in pseudo-polynomial time using dynamic programming.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] We define a *state* as a pair (*i*, *s*) of integers.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Starting from the initial state (0, 0), it is possible to use any graph search algorithm (e.g.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] If the state is found, then by backtracking we can find a subset with a sum of exactly *T*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The run-time of this algorithm is at most linear in the number of states.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The number of states is at most *N* times the number of different possible sums.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Let A be the sum of the negative values and B the sum of the positive values; the number of different possible sums is at most *B*-*A*, so the total runtime is in $O(N\cdot (B-A))$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] For example, if all input values are positive and bounded by some constant *C*, then *B* is at most *N C*, so the time required is $O(N^{2}C)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] This solution does not count as polynomial time in complexity theory because $B-A$ is not polynomial in the *size* of the problem, which is the number of bits used to represent it.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] This algorithm is polynomial in the values of A and B, which are exponential in their numbers of bits.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] However, Subset Sum encoded in *unary* is in P, since then the size of the encoding is linear in B-A.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Hence, Subset Sum is only *weakly* NP-Complete.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] For the case that each $x_{i}$ is positive and bounded by a fixed constant C, in 1999, Pisinger found a linear time algorithm having time complexity $O(NC)$ (note that this is for the version of the problem where the target sum is not necessarily zero, as otherwise the problem would be trivial).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] In 2015, Koiliaris and Xu found a deterministic ${\tilde {O}}(T{\sqrt {N}})$ algorithm for the subset sum problem where T is the sum we need to find.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] In 2017, Bringmann found a randomized ${\tilde {O}}(T+N)$ time algorithm.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] In 2014, Curtis and Sanches found a simple recursion highly scalable in SIMD machines having $O(N(m-x_{\min })/p)$ time and $O(N+m-x_{\min })$ space, where p is the number of processing elements, $m=\min(s,\sum x_{i}-s)$ and $x_{\min }$ is the lowest integer.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] This is the best theoretical parallel complexity known so far.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] A comparison of practical results and the solution of hard instances of the SSP is discussed by Curtis and Sanches.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] An approximation algorithm to SSP aims to find a subset of *S* with a sum of at most *T* and at least *r* times the optimal sum, where *r* is a number in (0,1) called the *approximation ratio*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] When this algorithm terminates, either all inputs are in the subset (which is obviously optimal), or there is an input that does not fit.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The first such input is smaller than all previous inputs that are in the subset and the sum of inputs in the subset is more than *T*/2 otherwise the input also is less than T/2 and it would fit in the set.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Such a sum greater than T/2 is obviously more than OPT/2.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The following algorithm attains, for every $\epsilon >0$ , an approximation ratio of $(1-\epsilon )$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Its run time is polynomial in n and $1/\epsilon$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Recall that *n* is the number of inputs and *T* is the upper bound to the subset sum.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Note that without the trimming step (the inner "for each" loop), the list *L* would contain the sums of all $2^{n}$ subsets of inputs.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] These properties together guarantee that the list L contains no more than $n/\epsilon$ elements; therefore the run-time is polynomial in $n/\epsilon$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] When the algorithm ends, if the optimal sum is in L, then it is returned and we are done.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Otherwise, it must have been removed in a previous trimming step.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Each trimming step introduces an additive error of at most $\epsilon T/n$ , so n steps together introduce an error of at most $\epsilon T$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Therefore, the returned solution is at least ${\text{OPT}}-\epsilon T$ which is at least $(1-\epsilon ){\text{OPT}}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] The above algorithm provides an *exact* solution to SSP in the case that the input numbers are small (and non-negative).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] If any sum of the numbers can be specified with at most P bits, then solving the problem approximately with $\epsilon =2^{-P}$ is equivalent to solving it exactly.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Then, the polynomial time algorithm for approximate subset sum becomes an exact algorithm with running time polynomial in n and $2^{P}$ (i.e., exponential in P).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/subset-sum-problem] Kellerer, Mansini, Pferschy and Speranza and Kellerer, Pferschy and Pisinger present other FPTASes for subset sum.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In theoretical computer science, the **time complexity** is the computational complexity that describes the amount of computer time it takes to run an algorithm.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Time complexity is commonly estimated by counting the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm, supposing that each elementary operation takes a fixed amount of time to perform.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Thus, the amount of time taken and the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm are taken to be related by a constant factor.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Since an algorithm's running time may vary among different inputs of the same size, one commonly considers the worst-case time complexity, which is the maximum amount of time required for inputs of a given size.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Less common, and usually specified explicitly, is the average-case complexity, which is the average of the time taken on inputs of a given size (this makes sense because there are only a finite number of possible inputs of a given size).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In both cases, the time complexity is generally expressed as a function of the size of the input.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Since this function is generally difficult to compute exactly, and the running time for small inputs is usually not consequential, one commonly focuses on the behavior of the complexity when the input size increases—that is, the asymptotic behavior of the complexity.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Therefore, the time complexity is commonly expressed using big O notation, typically $O(n)$ , $O(n\log n)$ , $O(n^{\alpha })$ , $O(2^{n})$ , etc., where n is the size in units of bits needed to represent the input.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Algorithmic complexities are classified according to the type of function appearing in the big O notation.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm with time complexity $O(n)$ is a *linear time algorithm* and an algorithm with time complexity $O(n^{\alpha })$ for some constant $\alpha >0$ is a *polynomial time algorithm*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The following table summarizes some classes of commonly encountered time complexities.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is termed **constant time** (often represented as ${\textstyle O(1)}$ time) when its complexity function ${\textstyle T(n)}$ is bounded by a value that does not change with the size of the input.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] This implies that the execution time remains consistent regardless of how much data is processed.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For instance, accessing a specific element in an array is a constant-time operation, as it requires only a single operation to locate that element.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In contrast, determining the minimum value in an unordered array is not constant time; it requires examining each element, resulting in linear time complexity, or ${\textstyle O(n)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] However, if the number of elements is known and fixed, certain tasks can still be considered constant time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Importantly, the term "constant time" does not mean the running time must be entirely independent of the problem size; rather, it should have a consistent upper bound irrespective of input size.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, a task that involves swapping the values of a and b to ensure ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ is classified as constant time, even if the execution time may vary depending on whether the condition is already met.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The key is that there exists a constant t such that the time taken will never exceed t, regardless of the input values.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Constant-time algorithms are especially significant in contexts like cryptography, where timing attacks can exploit variations in execution time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] By designing algorithms that run in constant time, developers can enhance security and ensure performance predictability, making it a fundamental consideration in software engineering.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **logarithmic time** when $T(n)=O(\log n)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Since $\log _{a}n$ and $\log _{b}n$ are related by a constant multiplier, and such a multiplier is irrelevant to big O classification, the standard usage for logarithmic-time algorithms is $O(\log n)$ regardless of the base of the logarithm appearing in the expression of T.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Algorithms taking logarithmic time are commonly found in operations on binary trees or when using binary search.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An $O(\log n)$ algorithm is considered highly efficient, as the ratio of the number of operations to the size of the input decreases and tends to zero when n increases.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm that must access all elements of its input cannot take logarithmic time, as the time taken for reading an input of size n is of the order of n.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An example of logarithmic time is given by dictionary search.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Consider a dictionary *D* which contains n entries, sorted in alphabetical order.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] We suppose that, for $1\leq k\leq n$ , one may access the kth entry of the dictionary in a constant time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Under these hypotheses, the test to see if a word w is in the dictionary may be done in logarithmic time: consider $D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ , where $\lfloor \;\rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] If $w=D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ --that is to say, the word w is exactly in the middle of the dictionary--then we are done.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Otherwise, if it comes after the middle word, continue similarly with the right half of the dictionary.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] This algorithm is similar to the method often used to find an entry in a paper dictionary.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] As a result, the search space within the dictionary decreases as the algorithm gets closer to the target word.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **polylogarithmic time** if its time $T(n)$ is $O{\bigl (}(\log n)^{k}{\bigr )}$ for some constant k.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Another way to write this is $O(\log ^{k}n)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, matrix chain ordering can be solved in polylogarithmic time on a parallel random-access machine, and a graph can be determined to be planar in a fully dynamic way in $O(\log ^{3}n)$ time per insert/delete operation.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **sub-linear time** (often spelled **sublinear time**) if $T(n)=o(n)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In particular this includes algorithms with the time complexities defined above.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The specific term *sublinear time algorithm* commonly refers to randomized algorithms that sample a small fraction of their inputs and process them efficiently to approximately infer properties of the entire instance.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] This type of sublinear time algorithm is closely related to property testing and statistics.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **linear time**, or $O(n)$ time, if its time complexity is $O(n)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Informally, this means that the running time increases at most linearly with the size of the input.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] More precisely, this means that there is a constant c such that the running time is at most $cn$ for every input of size n.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, a procedure that adds up all elements of a list requires time proportional to the length of the list, if the adding time is constant, or, at least, bounded by a constant.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Linear time is the best possible time complexity in situations where the algorithm has to sequentially read its entire input.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Therefore, much research has been invested into discovering algorithms exhibiting linear time or, at least, nearly linear time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] This research includes both software and hardware methods.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] There are several hardware technologies which exploit parallelism to provide this.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An example is content-addressable memory.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] This concept of linear time is used in string matching algorithms such as the Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and Ukkonen's algorithm.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **quasilinear time** (also referred to as **log-linear time**) if $T(n)=O(n\log ^{k}n)$ for some positive constant k; **linearithmic time** is the case $k=1$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Using soft O notation these algorithms are ${\tilde {O}}(n)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Quasilinear time algorithms are also $O(n^{1+\varepsilon })$ for every constant $\varepsilon >0$ and thus run faster than any polynomial time algorithm whose time bound includes a term $n^{c}$ for any $c>1$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In many cases, the $O(n\log n)$ running time is simply the result of performing a $\Theta (\log n)$ operation n times (for the notation, see Big O notation § Family of Bachmann–Landau notations).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, binary tree sort creates a binary tree by inserting each element of the n-sized array one by one.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Since the insert operation on a self-balancing binary search tree takes $O(\log n)$ time, the entire algorithm takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Comparison sorts require at least $\Omega (n\log n)$ comparisons in the worst case because $\log(n!)=\Theta (n\log n)$ , by Stirling's approximation.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] They also frequently arise from the recurrence relation ${\textstyle T(n)=2T\left({\frac {n}{2}}\right)+O(n)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **subquadratic time** if $T(n)=o(n^{2})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, simple, comparison-based sorting algorithms are quadratic (e.g. insertion sort), but more advanced algorithms can be found that are subquadratic (e.g. shell sort).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] No general-purpose sorts run in linear time, but the change from quadratic to sub-quadratic is of great practical importance.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be of **polynomial time** if its running time is upper bounded by a polynomial expression in the size of the input for the algorithm, that is, *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n**k*) for some positive constant *k*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Problems for which a deterministic polynomial-time algorithm exists belong to the complexity class **P**, which is central in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis states that polynomial time is a synonym for "tractable", "feasible", "efficient", or "fast".
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] These two concepts are only relevant if the inputs to the algorithms consist of integers.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The concept of polynomial time leads to several complexity classes in computational complexity theory.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Some important classes defined using polynomial time are the following.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] P is the smallest time-complexity class on a deterministic machine which is robust in terms of machine model changes.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is defined to take **superpolynomial time** if *T*(*n*) is not bounded above by any polynomial; that is, if ⁠ $T(n)\not \in O(n^{c})$ ⁠ for every positive integer *c*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm that runs for 2*n* steps on an input of size *n* requires superpolynomial time (more specifically, exponential time).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm that uses exponential resources is clearly superpolynomial, but some algorithms are only very weakly superpolynomial.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, the Adleman–Pomerance–Rumely primality test runs for *n**O*(log log *n*) time on *n*-bit inputs; this grows faster than any polynomial for large enough *n*, but the input size must become impractically large before it cannot be dominated by a polynomial with small degree.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm that requires superpolynomial time lies outside the complexity class **P**.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis posits that these algorithms are impractical, and in many cases they are.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Since the P versus NP problem is unresolved, it is unknown whether NP-complete problems require superpolynomial time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] There are some problems for which we know quasi-polynomial time algorithms, but no polynomial time algorithm is known.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Other computational problems with quasi-polynomial time solutions but no known polynomial time solution include the planted clique problem in which the goal is to find a large clique in the union of a clique and a random graph.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The complexity class **QP** consists of all problems that have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] It can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In complexity theory, the unsolved P versus NP problem asks if all problems in NP have polynomial-time algorithms.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] All the best-known algorithms for NP-complete problems like 3SAT etc. take exponential time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Indeed, it is conjectured for many natural NP-complete problems that they do not have sub-exponential time algorithms.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Here "sub-exponential time" is taken to mean the second definition presented below.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] (On the other hand, many graph problems represented in the natural way by adjacency matrices are solvable in subexponential time simply because the size of the input is the square of the number of vertices.) This conjecture (for the k-SAT problem) is known as the exponential time hypothesis.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Since it is conjectured that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms, some inapproximability results in the field of approximation algorithms make the assumption that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, see the known inapproximability results for the set cover problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The term **sub-exponential time** is used to express that the running time of some algorithm may grow faster than any polynomial but is still significantly smaller than an exponential.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In this sense, problems that have sub-exponential time algorithms are somewhat more tractable than those that only have exponential algorithms.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The precise definition of "sub-exponential" is not generally agreed upon, however the two most widely used are below.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] A problem is said to be sub-exponential time solvable if it can be solved in running times whose logarithms grow smaller than any given polynomial.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] More precisely, a problem is in sub-exponential time if for every *ε* > 0 there exists an algorithm which solves the problem in time *O*(2*n**ε*).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The set of all such problems is the complexity class **SUBEXP** which can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] This notion of sub-exponential is non-uniform in terms of *ε* in the sense that *ε* is not part of the input and each ε may have its own algorithm for the problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Some authors define sub-exponential time as running times in $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] This definition allows larger running times than the first definition of sub-exponential time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An example of such a sub-exponential time algorithm is the best-known classical algorithm for integer factorization, the general number field sieve, which runs in time about $2^{{O}(n^{1/3}(\log n)^{2/3})}$ , where the length of the input is n.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Another example was the graph isomorphism problem, which the best known algorithm from 1982 to 2016 solved in $2^{O\left({\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)}$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] However, at STOC 2016 a quasi-polynomial time algorithm was presented.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] It makes a difference whether the algorithm is allowed to be sub-exponential in the size of the instance, the number of vertices, or the number of edges.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In parameterized complexity, this difference is made explicit by considering pairs $(L,k)$ of decision problems and parameters *k*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] More precisely, SUBEPT is the class of all parameterized problems $(L,k)$ for which there is a computable function $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ with $f\in o(k)$ and an algorithm that decides *L* in time $2^{f(k)}\cdot {\textsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The **exponential time hypothesis** (**ETH**) is that 3SAT, the satisfiability problem of Boolean formulas in conjunctive normal form with at most three literals per clause and with *n* variables, cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*n*).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] More precisely, the hypothesis is that there is some absolute constant *c* > 0 such that 3SAT cannot be decided in time 2*cn* by any deterministic Turing machine.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] With *m* denoting the number of clauses, ETH is equivalent to the hypothesis that *k*SAT cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*m*) for any integer *k* ≥ 3.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] The exponential time hypothesis implies P ≠ NP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **exponential time**, if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 2poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] More formally, an algorithm is exponential time if *T*(*n*) is bounded by *O*(2*n**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Problems which admit exponential time algorithms on a deterministic Turing machine form the complexity class known as **EXP**.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Sometimes, exponential time is used to refer to algorithms that have *T*(*n*) = 2*O*(*n*), where the exponent is at most a linear function of *n*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] This gives rise to the complexity class **E**.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **factorial time** if *T(n)* is upper bounded by the factorial function *n!*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Factorial time is a subset of exponential time (EXP) because $n!\leq n^{n}=2^{n\log n}=O\left(2^{n^{1+\epsilon }}\right)$ for all $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An example of an algorithm that runs in factorial time is bogosort, a notoriously inefficient sorting algorithm based on trial and error.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Bogosort sorts a list of *n* items by repeatedly shuffling the list until it is found to be sorted.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] In the average case, each pass through the bogosort algorithm will examine one of the *n*! orderings of the *n* items.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] If the items are distinct, only one such ordering is sorted.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Bogosort shares patrimony with the infinite monkey theorem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be double exponential time if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 22poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/time-complexity] Such algorithms belong to the complexity class 2-EXPTIME.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The travelling purchaser problem, the vehicle routing problem and the ring star problem are three generalizations of TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The decision version of the TSP (where given a length *L*, the task is to decide whether the graph has a tour whose length is at most *L*) belongs to the class of NP-complete problems.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Thus, it is possible that the worst-case running time for any algorithm for the TSP increases superpolynomially (but no more than exponentially) with the number of cities.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem was first formulated in 1930 and is one of the most intensively studied problems in optimization.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] It is used as a benchmark for many optimization methods.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Even though the problem is computationally difficult, many heuristics and exact algorithms are known, so that some instances with tens of thousands of cities can be solved completely, and even problems with millions of cities can be approximated within a small fraction of 1%.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP has several applications even in its purest formulation, such as planning, logistics, and the manufacture of microchips.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In warehouse operations, order picking routes are often modelled as variants of the travelling salesman problem, where a picker must visit multiple storage locations and return to a start or drop-off point while minimizing travel distance or time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Slightly modified, it appears as a sub-problem in many areas, such as DNA sequencing.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In these applications, the concept *city* represents, for example, customers, soldering points, or DNA fragments, and the concept *distance* represents travelling times or cost, or a similarity measure between DNA fragments.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP also appears in astronomy, as astronomers observing many sources want to minimize the time spent moving the telescope between the sources; in such problems, the TSP can be embedded inside an optimal control problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In many applications, additional constraints such as limited resources or time windows may be imposed.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The origins of the travelling salesman problem are unclear.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] A handbook for travelling salesmen from 1832 mentions the problem and includes example tours through Germany and Switzerland, but contains no mathematical treatment.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP was mathematically formulated in the 19th century by the Irish mathematician William Rowan Hamilton and by the British mathematician Thomas Kirkman.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Hamilton's icosian game was a recreational puzzle based on finding a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] It was first considered mathematically in the 1930s by Merrill M.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Flood, who was looking to solve a school bus routing problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Hassler Whitney at Princeton University generated interest in the problem, which he called the "48 states problem".
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the 1950s and 1960s, the problem became increasingly popular in scientific circles in Europe and the United States after the RAND Corporation in Santa Monica offered prizes for steps in solving the problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Notable contributions were made by George Dantzig, Delbert Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Johnson from the RAND Corporation, who expressed the problem as an integer linear program and developed the cutting plane method for its solution.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] They wrote what is considered the seminal paper on the subject in which, with these new methods, they solved an instance with 49 cities to optimality by constructing a tour and proving that no other tour could be shorter.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson, however, speculated that, given a near-optimal solution, one may be able to find optimality or prove optimality by adding a small number of extra inequalities (cuts).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] They used this idea to solve their initial 49-city problem using a string model.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] They found they only needed 26 cuts to come to a solution for their 49 city problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] While this paper did not give an algorithmic approach to TSP problems, the ideas that lay within it were indispensable to later creating exact solution methods for the TSP, though it would take 15 years to find an algorithmic approach in creating these cuts.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] As well as cutting plane methods, Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson used branch-and-bound algorithms perhaps for the first time.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Halton, and John Hammersley published an article entitled "The Shortest Path Through Many Points" in the journal of the Cambridge Philosophical Society.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The Beardwood–Halton–Hammersley theorem provides a practical solution to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The authors derived an asymptotic formula to determine the length of the shortest route for a salesman who starts at a home or office and visits a fixed number of locations before returning to the start.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the following decades, the problem was studied by many researchers from mathematics, computer science, chemistry, physics, and other sciences.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] One method of doing this was to create a minimum spanning tree of the graph and then double all its edges, which produces the bound that the length of an optimal tour is at most twice the weight of a minimum spanning tree.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In 1976, Christofides and Serdyukov (independently of each other) made a big advance in this direction: the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm yields a solution that, in the worst case, is at most 1.5 times longer than the optimal solution.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] As the algorithm was simple and quick, many hoped it would give way to a near-optimal solution method.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] However, this hope for improvement did not immediately materialize, and the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm remained the method with the best worst-case scenario until 2011, when a (very) slightly improved approximation algorithm was developed for the subset of "graphical" TSPs.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In 2020, this tiny improvement was extended to the full (metric) TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Karp showed in 1972 that the Hamiltonian cycle problem was NP-complete, which implies the NP-hardness of TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This supplied a mathematical explanation for the apparent computational difficulty of finding optimal tours.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Great progress was made in the late 1970s and 1980, when Grötschel, Padberg, Rinaldi and others managed to exactly solve instances with up to 2,392 cities, using cutting planes and branch-and-bound.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the 1990s, Applegate, Bixby, Chvátal, and Cook developed the program *Concorde* that has been used in many recent record solutions.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Gerhard Reinelt published the TSPLIB in 1991, a collection of benchmark instances of varying difficulty, which has been used by many research groups for comparing results.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In 2006, Cook and others computed an optimal tour through an 85,900-city instance given by a microchip layout problem, currently the largest solved TSPLIB instance.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For many other instances with millions of cities, solutions can be found that are guaranteed to be within 2–3% of an optimal tour.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP can be modeled as an undirected weighted graph, such that cities are the graph's vertices, paths are the graph's edges, and a path's distance is the edge's weight.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] It is a minimization problem starting and finishing at a specified vertex after having visited each other vertex exactly once.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Often, the model is a complete graph (i.e., each pair of vertices is connected by an edge).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] If no path exists between two cities, then adding a sufficiently long edge will complete the graph without affecting the optimal tour.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *symmetric TSP*, the distance between two cities is the same in each opposite direction, forming an undirected graph.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This symmetry halves the number of possible solutions.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *asymmetric TSP*, paths may not exist in both directions or the distances might be different, forming a directed graph.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Traffic congestion, one-way streets, and airfares for cities with different departure and arrival fees are real-world considerations that could yield a TSP problem in asymmetric form.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP can be formulated as an integer linear program.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Two notable formulations are the Miller–Tucker–Zemlin (MTZ) formulation and the Dantzig–Fulkerson–Johnson (DFJ) formulation.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The DFJ formulation is stronger, though the MTZ formulation is still useful in certain settings.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Common to both these formulations is that one labels the cities with the numbers $1,\ldots ,n$ and takes $c_{ij}>0$ to be the cost (distance) from city i to city j .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] It is because these are 0/1 variables that the formulations become integer programs; all other constraints are purely linear.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Without further constraints, the $\{x_{ij}\}_{i,j}$ will effectively range over all subsets of the set of edges, which is very far from the sets of edges in a tour, and allows for a trivial minimum where all $x_{ij}=0$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The MTZ and DFJ formulations differ in how they express this final requirement as linear constraints.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Merely requiring $u_{j}\geq u_{i}+x_{ij}$ would *not* achieve that, because this also requires $u_{j}\geq u_{i}$ when $x_{ij}=0,$ which is not correct.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The first set of equalities requires that each city is arrived at from exactly one other city, and the second set of equalities requires that from each city there is a departure to exactly one other city.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The last constraint enforces that there is only a single tour covering all cities, and not two or more disjointed tours that only collectively cover all cities.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Take $c_{ij}>0$ to be the distance from city *i* to city *j*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The last constraint of the DFJ formulation—called a *subtour elimination* constraint—ensures that no proper subset Q can form a sub-tour, so the solution returned is a single tour and not the union of smaller tours.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Intuitively, for each proper subset Q of the cities, the constraint requires that there be fewer edges than cities in Q: if there were to be as many edges in Q as cities in Q, that would represent a subtour of the cities of Q.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Because this leads to an exponential number of possible constraints, in practice it is solved with row generation.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The most direct solution would be to try all permutations (ordered combinations) and see which one is cheapest (using brute-force search).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The running time for this approach lies within a polynomial factor of $O(n!)$ , the factorial of the number of cities, so this solution becomes impractical even for only 20 cities.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] One of the earliest applications of dynamic programming is the Held–Karp algorithm, which solves the problem in time $O(n^{2}2^{n})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Improving these time bounds seems to be difficult.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, it has not been determined whether a classical exact algorithm for TSP that runs in time $O(1.9999^{n})$ exists.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The currently best quantum exact algorithm for TSP due to Ambainis et al. runs in time $O(1.728^{n})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] An exact solution for 15,112 German towns from TSPLIB was found in 2001 using the cutting-plane method proposed by George Dantzig, Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Johnson in 1954, based on linear programming.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The computations were performed on a network of 110 processors located at Rice University and Princeton University.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The total computation time was equivalent to 22.6 years on a single 500 MHz Alpha processor.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In May 2004, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 24,978 towns in Sweden was solved: a tour of length approximately 72,500 kilometres was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In March 2005, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 33,810 points in a circuit board was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*: a tour of length 66,048,945 units was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The computation took approximately 15.7 CPU-years (Cook et al.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In April 2006 an instance with 85,900 points was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*, taking over 136 CPU-years; see Applegate et al.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Various heuristics and approximation algorithms, which quickly yield good solutions, have been devised.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] These include the multi-fragment algorithm.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Modern methods can find solutions for extremely large problems (millions of cities) within a reasonable time which are, with a high probability, just 2–3% away from the optimal solution.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Several categories of heuristics are recognized.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The nearest neighbour (NN) algorithm (a greedy algorithm) lets the salesman choose the nearest unvisited city as his next move.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This algorithm quickly yields an effectively short route.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For *N* cities randomly distributed on a plane, the algorithm on average yields a path 25% longer than the shortest possible path; however, there exist many specially-arranged city distributions which make the NN algorithm give the worst route.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This is true for both asymmetric and symmetric TSPs.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Rosenkrantz et al. showed that the NN algorithm has the approximation factor $\Theta (\log |V|)$ for instances satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] A variation of the NN algorithm, called nearest fragment (NF) operator, which connects a group (fragment) of nearest unvisited cities, can find shorter routes with successive iterations.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The NF operator can also be applied on an initial solution obtained by the NN algorithm for further improvement in an elitist model, where only better solutions are accepted.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The bitonic tour of a set of points is the minimum-perimeter monotone polygon that has the points as its vertices; it can be computed efficiently with dynamic programming.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Another constructive heuristic, Match Twice and Stitch (MTS), performs two sequential matchings, where the second matching is executed after deleting all the edges of the first matching, to yield a set of cycles.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The cycles are then stitched to produce the final tour.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov follows a similar outline but combines the minimum spanning tree with a solution of another problem, minimum-weight perfect matching.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This gives a TSP tour which is at most 1.5 times the optimal.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] It was one of the first approximation algorithms, and was in part responsible for drawing attention to approximation algorithms as a practical approach to intractable problems.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] As a matter of fact, the term "algorithm" was not commonly extended to approximation algorithms until later; the Christofides algorithm was initially referred to as the Christofides heuristic.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This algorithm looks at things differently by using a result from graph theory which helps improve on the lower bound of the TSP which originated from doubling the cost of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Given an Eulerian graph, we can find an Eulerian tour in ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, so if we had an Eulerian graph with cities from a TSP as vertices, then we can easily see that we could use such a method for finding an Eulerian tour to find a TSP solution.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] By the triangle inequality, we know that the TSP tour can be no longer than the Eulerian tour, and we therefore have a lower bound for the TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Create duplicates for every edge to create an Eulerian graph.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Convert to TSP: if a city is visited twice, then create a shortcut from the city before this in the tour to the one after this.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] To improve the lower bound, a better way of creating an Eulerian graph is needed.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] By the triangle inequality, the best Eulerian graph must have the same cost as the best travelling salesman tour; hence, finding optimal Eulerian graphs is at least as hard as TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] One way of doing this is by minimum weight matching using algorithms with a complexity of $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Making a graph into an Eulerian graph starts with the minimum spanning tree; all the vertices of odd order must then be made even, so a matching for the odd-degree vertices must be added, which increases the order of every odd-degree vertex by 1.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This leaves us with a graph where every vertex is of even order, which is thus Eulerian.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Create a matching for the problem with the set of cities of odd order.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The pairwise exchange or 2-opt technique involves iteratively removing two edges and replacing them with two different edges that reconnect the fragments created by edge removal into a new and shorter tour.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Similarly, the 3-opt technique removes 3 edges and reconnects them to form a shorter tour.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] These are special cases of the *k*-opt method.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The label *Lin–Kernighan* is an often heard misnomer for 2-opt; Lin–Kernighan is actually the more general *k*-opt method.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For Euclidean instances, 2-opt heuristics give on average solutions that are about 5% better than those yielded by Christofides' algorithm.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] If we start with an initial solution made with a greedy algorithm, then the average number of moves greatly decreases again and is ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠; however, for random starts, the average number of moves is ⁠ $O(n\log(n))$ ⁠.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] While this is a small increase in size, the initial number of moves for small problems is 10 times as big for a random start compared to one made from a greedy heuristic.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This is because such 2-opt heuristics exploit 'bad' parts of a solution such as crossings.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] These types of heuristics are often used within vehicle routing problem heuristics to re-optimize route solutions.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The Lin–Kernighan heuristic is a special case of the *V*-opt or variable-opt technique.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Reassemble the remaining fragments into a tour, leaving no disjoint subtours (that is, do not connect a fragment's endpoints together).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This in effect simplifies the TSP under consideration into a much simpler problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Each fragment endpoint can be connected to 2*k* − 2 other possibilities: of 2*k* total fragment endpoints available, the two endpoints of the fragment under consideration are disallowed.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Such a constrained 2*k*-city TSP can then be solved with brute-force methods to find the least-cost recombination of the original fragments.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The most popular of the *k*-opt methods are 3-opt, as introduced by Shen Lin of Bell Labs in 1965.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] A special case of 3-opt is where the edges are not disjoint (two of the edges are adjacent to one another).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In practice, it is often possible to achieve substantial improvement over 2-opt without the combinatorial cost of the general 3-opt by restricting the 3-changes to this special subset where two of the removed edges are adjacent.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This so-called two-and-a-half-opt typically falls roughly midway between 2-opt and 3-opt, both in terms of the quality of tours achieved and the time required to achieve those tours.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The variable-opt method is related to, and a generalization of, the *k*-opt method.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Whereas the *k*-opt methods remove a fixed number (*k*) of edges from the original tour, the variable-opt methods do not fix the size of the edge set to remove.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Instead, they grow the set as the search process continues.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The best-known method in this family is the Lin–Kernighan method (mentioned above as a misnomer for 2-opt).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Shen Lin and Brian Kernighan first published their method in 1972, and it was the most reliable heuristic for solving travelling salesman problems for nearly two decades.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] More advanced variable-opt methods were developed at Bell Labs in the late 1980s by David Johnson and his research team.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] These methods (sometimes called Lin–Kernighan–Johnson) build on the Lin–Kernighan method, adding ideas from tabu search and evolutionary computing.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The basic Lin–Kernighan technique gives results that are guaranteed to be at least 3-opt.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The Lin–Kernighan–Johnson methods compute a Lin–Kernighan tour, and then perturb the tour by what has been described as a mutation that removes at least four edges and reconnects the tour in a different way, then *V*-opting the new tour.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The mutation is often enough to move the tour from the local minimum identified by Lin–Kernighan.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] *V*-opt methods are widely considered the most powerful heuristics for the problem, and are able to address special cases, such as the Hamilton Cycle Problem and other non-metric TSPs that other heuristics fail on.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For many years, Lin–Kernighan–Johnson had identified optimal solutions for all TSPs where an optimal solution was known and had identified the best-known solutions for all other TSPs on which the method had been tried.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Optimized Markov chain algorithms which use local searching heuristic sub-algorithms can find a route extremely close to the optimal route for 700 to 800 cities.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP is a touchstone for many general heuristics devised for combinatorial optimization such as genetic algorithms, simulated annealing, tabu search, ant colony optimization, river formation dynamics (see swarm intelligence), and the cross entropy method.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This starts with a sub-tour such as the convex hull and then inserts other vertices.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Artificial intelligence researcher Marco Dorigo described in 1993 a method of heuristically generating "good solutions" to the TSP using a simulation of an ant colony called *ACS* (*ant colony system*).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] It models behavior observed in real ants to find short paths between food sources and their nest, an emergent behavior resulting from each ant's preference to follow trail pheromones deposited by other ants.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] ACS sends out a large number of virtual ant agents to explore many possible routes on the map.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Each ant probabilistically chooses the next city to visit based on a heuristic combining the distance to the city and the amount of virtual pheromone deposited on the edge to the city.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The ants explore, depositing pheromone on each edge that they cross, until they have all completed a tour.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] At this point the ant which completed the shortest tour deposits virtual pheromone along its complete tour route (*global trail updating*).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The amount of pheromone deposited is inversely proportional to the tour length: the shorter the tour, the more it deposits.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *metric TSP*, also known as *delta-TSP* or Δ-TSP, the intercity distances satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The edges then build a metric on the set of vertices.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] When the cities are viewed as points in the plane, many natural distance functions are metrics, and so many natural instances of TSP satisfy this constraint.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The following are some examples of metric TSPs for various metrics.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The last two metrics appear, for example, in routing a machine that drills a given set of holes in a printed circuit board.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The Manhattan metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts first one coordinate, and then the other, so the time to move to a new point is the sum of both movements.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The maximum metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts both coordinates simultaneously, so the time to move to a new point is the slower of the two movements.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In its definition, the TSP does not allow cities to be visited twice, but many applications do not need this constraint.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In such cases, a symmetric, non-metric instance can be reduced to a metric one.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This replaces the original graph with a complete graph in which the inter-city distance $d_{AB}$ is replaced by the shortest path length between *A* and *B* in the original graph.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For points in the Euclidean plane, the optimal solution to the travelling salesman problem forms a simple polygon through all of the points, a polygonalization of the points.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Any non-optimal solution with crossings can be made into a shorter solution without crossings by local optimizations.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The Euclidean distance obeys the triangle inequality, so the Euclidean TSP forms a special case of metric TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] However, even when the input points have integer coordinates, their distances generally take the form of square roots, and the length of a tour is a sum of radicals, making it difficult to perform the symbolic computation needed to perform exact comparisons of the lengths of different tours.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Like the general TSP, the exact Euclidean TSP is NP-hard, but the issue with sums of radicals is an obstacle to proving that its decision version is in NP, and therefore NP-complete.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] A discretized version of the problem with distances rounded to integers is NP-complete.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] With rational coordinates and the actual Euclidean metric, Euclidean TSP is known to be in the Counting Hierarchy, a subclass of PSPACE.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] With arbitrary real coordinates, Euclidean TSP cannot be in such classes, since there are uncountably many possible inputs.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Despite these complications, Euclidean TSP is much easier than the general metric case for approximation.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, the minimum spanning tree of the graph associated with an instance of the Euclidean TSP is a Euclidean minimum spanning tree, and so can be computed in expected *O*(*n* log *n*) time for *n* points (considerably less than the number of edges).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This enables the simple 2-approximation algorithm for TSP with triangle inequality above to operate more quickly.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] time; this is called a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Mitchell were awarded the Gödel Prize in 2010 for their concurrent discovery of a PTAS for the Euclidean TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In practice, simpler heuristics with weaker guarantees continue to be used.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In most cases, the distance between two nodes in the TSP network is the same in both directions.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The case where the distance from *A* to *B* is not equal to the distance from *B* to *A* is called asymmetric TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] A practical application of an asymmetric TSP is route optimization using street-level routing (which is made asymmetric by one-way streets, slip-roads, motorways, etc.).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The stacker crane problem can be viewed as a special case of the asymmetric TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In this problem, the input consists of ordered pairs of points in a metric space, which must be visited consecutively in order by the tour.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] These pairs of points can be viewed as the nodes of an asymmetric TSP, with asymmetric distances reflecting the combined cost of traveling from the first point of a pair to its second and then from the second point of a pair to the first point of the next pair.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Solving an asymmetric TSP graph can be somewhat complex.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The following is a 3×3 matrix containing all possible path weights between the nodes *A*, *B* and *C*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] One option is to turn an asymmetric matrix of size *N* into a symmetric matrix of size 2*N*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] To double the size, each of the nodes in the graph is duplicated, creating a second *ghost node*, linked to the original node with a "ghost" edge of very low (possibly negative) weight, here denoted −*w*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] (Alternatively, the ghost edges have weight 0, and weight w is added to all other edges.) The original 3×3 matrix shown above is visible in the bottom left and the transpose of the original in the top-right.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Both copies of the matrix have had their diagonals replaced by the low-cost hop paths, represented by −*w*.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the new graph, no edge directly links original nodes and no edge directly links ghost nodes.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The weight −*w* of the "ghost" edges linking the ghost nodes to the corresponding original nodes must be low enough to ensure that all ghost edges must belong to any optimal symmetric TSP solution on the new graph (*w* = 0 is not always low enough).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] There is an analogous problem in geometric measure theory which asks the following: under what conditions may a subset *E* of Euclidean space be contained in a rectifiable curve (that is, when is there a curve with finite length that visits every point in *E*)?
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This problem is known as the analyst's travelling salesman problem.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Suppose $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are n independent random variables with uniform distribution in the square $[0,1]^{2}$ , and let $L_{n}^{\ast }$ be the shortest path length (i.e.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP solution) for this set of points, according to the usual Euclidean distance.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] where $\beta$ is a positive constant that is not known explicitly.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Since $L_{n}^{*}\leq 2{\sqrt {n}}+2$ (see below), it follows from bounded convergence theorem that $\beta =\lim _{n\to \infty }\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]/{\sqrt {n}}$ , hence lower and upper bounds on $\beta$ follow from bounds on $\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The almost-sure limit ${\frac {L_{n}^{*}}{\sqrt {n}}}\rightarrow \beta$ as $n\to \infty$ may not exist if the independent locations $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are replaced with observations from a stationary ergodic process with uniform marginals.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Held and Karp gave a polynomial-time algorithm that provides numerical lower bounds for $L_{n}^{*}$ , and thus for $\beta (\simeq L_{n}^{*}/{\sqrt {n}})$ , which seem to be good up to more or less 1%.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] where 0.522 comes from the points near the square boundary which have fewer neighbours, and Christine L.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem has been shown to be NP-hard (more precisely, it is complete for the complexity class FPNP; see function problem), and the decision problem version ("given the costs and a number *x*, decide whether there is a round-trip route cheaper than *x*") is NP-complete.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The bottleneck travelling salesman problem is also NP-hard.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem remains NP-hard even for the case when the cities are in the plane with Euclidean distances, as well as in a number of other restrictive cases.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Removing the condition of visiting each city "only once" does not remove the NP-hardness, since in the planar case there is an optimal tour that visits each city only once (otherwise, by the triangle inequality, a shortcut that skips a repeated visit would not increase the tour length).
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the general case, finding a shortest travelling salesman tour is NPO-complete.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance measure is a metric (and thus symmetric), the problem becomes APX-complete, and the algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov approximates it within 1.5.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distances are restricted to 1 and 2 (but still are a metric), then the approximation ratio becomes 8/7.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the asymmetric case with triangle inequality, in 2018, a constant factor approximation was developed by Svensson, Tarnawski, and Végh.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] An algorithm by Vera Traub and Jens Vygen achieves a performance ratio of $22+\varepsilon$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This factor was further improved to $17+\varepsilon$ .
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The best known inapproximability bound is 75/74.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The corresponding maximization problem of finding the *longest* travelling salesman tour is approximable within 63/38.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance function is symmetric, then the longest tour can be approximated within 4/3 by a deterministic algorithm and within $(33+\varepsilon )/25$ by a randomized algorithm.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP, in particular the Euclidean variant of the problem, has attracted the attention of researchers in cognitive psychology.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] It has been observed that humans are able to produce near-optimal solutions quickly, in a close-to-linear fashion, with performance that ranges from 1% less efficient, for graphs with 10–20 nodes, to 11% less efficient for graphs with 120 nodes.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The apparent ease with which humans accurately generate near-optimal solutions to the problem has led researchers to hypothesize that humans use one or more heuristics, with the two most popular theories arguably being the convex-hull hypothesis and the crossing-avoidance heuristic.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] However, additional evidence suggests that human performance is quite varied, and individual differences as well as graph geometry appear to affect performance in the task.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Nevertheless, results suggest that computer performance on the TSP may be improved by understanding and emulating the methods used by humans for these problems, and have also led to new insights into the mechanisms of human thought.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The first issue of the *Journal of Problem Solving* was devoted to the topic of human performance on TSP, and a 2011 review listed dozens of papers on the subject.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the first experiment, pigeons were placed in the corner of a lab room and allowed to fly to nearby feeders containing peas.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] The researchers found that pigeons largely used proximity to determine which feeder they would select next.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] In the second experiment, the feeders were arranged in such a way that flying to the nearest feeder at every opportunity would be largely inefficient if the pigeons needed to visit every feeder.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] This suggests non-primates may possess a relatively sophisticated spatial cognitive ability.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Humans are not the only species to show excellent efficiency.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, when presented with a spatial configuration of food sources, the amoeboid *Physarum polycephalum* adapts its morphology to create an efficient path between the food sources, which can also be viewed as an approximate solution to TSP.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Similarly, honey bees and bumblebees have been shown to be very adept at maximising efficiency to a very high degree of accuracy when collecting nectar and pollen by using collective intelligence.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] For benchmarking of TSP algorithms, TSPLIB is a library of sample instances of the TSP and related problems.
[src:exponential-time-algorithms/travelling-salesman-problem] Many of them are lists of actual cities and layouts of actual printed circuits.
